##Liang Hong: "New Crown" epidemic on the overall impact of China's economy may not exceed "SARS"

I-CAIJING

To its credit, the policy response to the outbreak has been decisive and effective. But the outbreak also highlights some areas of China's health care system that remain to be improved, including chronic shortages of health care workers and related supplies

By Liang Hong

As of 2400 hours on February 4,24,324 cases of COVID-19 pneumonia had been confirmed in mainland China, bringing the total number of suspected cases to 23,260. Although there are still many uncertainties about the rapid evolution of events, the duration and scope of the epidemic, it is not difficult to summarize the following two common features from the experience of similar epidemics in modern history, first, the impact of the epidemic on economic activity is temporary; Second, the government tends to increase counter-cyclical regulation to mitigate its impact on economic growth and the corporate sector.

Under the baseline situation, we expect the "new crown" epidemic to enter a "remission period" around mid-february, that is, the daily new cases began to decrease, and entered a "plateau period" , that is, new cases, at the end of February / early March, the number of confirmed cases dropped to "sporadic" levels. Our judgment mainly refers to the 2003 implementation of strict quarantine measures, the evolution of the SARS epidemic. However, if there is a tail risk such as a mutation of the virus or a "secondary outbreak" , the impact on economic activity is likely to be greater and more lasting.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
But there is no denying that strict quarantine measures, while essential in terms of containing the spread of the epidemic, will have a more pronounced impact on growth in the short term, enterprises with high operating or financial leverage, offline service industry, and small and medium-sized enterprises with limited financing channels will face greater cash flow pressure.

How will this epidemic evolve?

After strict quarantine measures are implemented, the number of newly diagnosed cases is expected to decrease within 2 weeks, and then drop to "sporadic" level after 2-3 weeks. Admittedly, infectious disease research is not our area of expertise, and the current epidemic is still in its early stages, but in order to make some general judgments about economic trends as early as possible, we are trying to make some common sense assessment of the evolution of this "new crown" epidemic. The main basis for our assessment is the evolution of the SARS epidemic in 2003 following strict quarantine measures.

Referring to the evolution of the SARS epidemic in 2003, under the baseline situation, we expect the "new crown" epidemic situation to enter a "remission period" around mid-february (that is, the daily number of new cases begins to decrease) , it entered a "plateau" in late February / early March, when the number of new diagnoses fell to a "sporadic" level. In order to prevent the spread of the "new crown" epidemic, Wuhan on January 24,2020 closed the channel from the city, marking the beginning of a wide range of strict isolation measures. Similar measures have since been taken in the surrounding cities of Wuhan, with a significant escalation of nationwide prevention and control measures, including the extension of the Spring Festival holiday, the delayed opening of schools and the temporary closure of public facilities such as entertainment venues. In line with the escalation of SARS prevention and control measures, we have observed a "third-order derivative decline" , that is, the rate of increase in newly confirmed cases began to slow down on January 28, indicating that the epidemic may have entered a "preliminary control period. ".

If the next development of this epidemic is broadly in line with the trajectory of SARS, so, on the premise of proper prevention and control, we believe that the absolute number of newly diagnosed cases will begin to decline in mid-february. The outbreak is expected to enter a "plateau" , a prelude to containment, as early as a month after the strong quarantine measures went into effect. In the light of experience during the SARS period, travel restrictions may be gradually lifted and business activity may begin to recover a month after the start of the platform period.

The economic impact of the "new crown" epidemic may not exceed that of "SARS"

Despite the fact that each epidemic has a different evolutionary path, it is not difficult to draw two common features from the experience of similar outbreaks in modern history:

First, the epidemic may have obvious effects on economic activity, but these effects are always temporary. In a recent report, we review the economic impact of SARS in 2003 -- until the second quarter of 2003. In the history of modern medicine, the impact of an epidemic on the local economy usually lasts only a quarter or two.

Second, the government tends to increase counter-cyclical adjustment in order to mitigate the impact on economic growth, household income and corporate cash flow. We believe that during the epidemic, the government should take measures to maintain reasonably ample liquidity and stable growth expectations to prevent the corporate sector from falling into a "liquidity crisis" due to a temporary and sharp contraction in aggregate demand.

Although it is too early to make a definitive judgment, but in the baseline situation, "new crown" epidemic on the overall impact of the economy may not be more than "SARS.

Economic observers and market participants tend to be pessimistic about the evolution of the "new crown" epidemic and its economic impact when there is still a high degree of uncertainty about its development. However, if we look ahead and see the development of the epidemic broadly in line with our baseline scenario, it may be premature to say that the overall economic impact of the "new crown" epidemic is higher than that of "SARS" for the following reasons:

First, the impact of the outbreak may be short-lived. As we have analyzed in the previous section, compared with SARS, this strict isolation defense measure "new crown" was adopted earlier and on a larger scale, as a result, the "new crown" outbreak may enter a "remission" period of time is shorter than "SARS" (from the first case of SARS infection confirmed to strict quarantine measures lasted for five months) . In addition, the fight against SARS has brought valuable experience, prompting the fight against the epidemic to take a series of measures such as isolation, quarantine and prevention more decisive, strong, therefore, the prevention and control of the epidemic is also expected to be more effective.

Second, the impact of the massive quarantine measures was concentrated in january-february, while SARS had its greatest impact on the economy in april-may. As a result, the "period" affected by the outbreak accounts for a relatively small proportion of total annual output, especially for indicators such as investment, trade and industrial production. Although the outbreak of the "new crown" epidemic occurred in the early stage of the Spring Festival travel period, making it more difficult to prevent and control the epidemic, the epidemic was effectively contained under our baseline hypothesis, that is, by the end of February, the outbreak control period was not entirely unrewarding -- as total output in january-february was the smallest proportion of the year, with part of the "quarantine period" falling during periods of significant decline in economic activity of its own. In april-may 2003, SARS had the greatest impact on economic activity, which was also the "peak season" for investment and industrial production. January-february represented a smaller share of annual output than april-may.

On a slightly longer-term basis, the impact of SARS on real and nominal GDP growth was concentrated in the second quarter of 2003, after which growth picked up significantly in the third quarter. Based on our baseline scenario, the impact of this outbreak on GDP this year is likely to be concentrated in the first quarter. Comparing the first and second quarters, january-february and april-may, the proportion of total demand and various sub-indicators in the whole year accounted for about 22% of total GDP in the first quarter, and about 25% of total GDP in the second quarter. In addition, january-february accounted for a smaller share of total output for the year as a result of the long Lunar New Year holiday.

Thirdly, so far, the impact of the epidemic has been concentrated in Hubei Province, while the SARS period was a "multi-point outbreak" situation, when the epidemic spread to a number of provinces and other countries only after attention. During the SARS period, 10 provinces and cities in mainland China were defined as "epidemic areas" by World Health Organization organization, including many important economic and trade cities —— which together accounted for over 40% of GDP and nearly 60% of trade. This time Hubei province accounted for about 60% of all "new crown" confirmed cases, but also the most stringent quarantine measures in the province. Yet Hubei accounts for only 4.3 per cent of GDP and less than 2 per cent of exports. If the epidemic situation of "new crown" can be controlled effectively in the provinces and cities outside Hubei according to the current trend, the economic vitality of most areas of the country may be restored earlier and faster than during the SARS period.

Finally, there is scope for both monetary and fiscal policy to increase counter-cyclical regulation, especially given that the outbreak occurred early in the year (and before the NPC and CPPCC targets were set) . The policy responses during SARS showed that countercyclical adjustment policies, especially monetary policy, were significantly overweighted during the epidemic. Thus, although demand was temporarily subdued, the growth of money and credit accelerated. The loose policy environment during the SARS period led to the rapid recovery of economic activities after the SARS epidemic. The Central Bank and other departments jointly issued a notice on February 1, saying they would maintain reasonable and ample liquidity while providing support to enterprises affected by the epidemic by reducing the cost of loans, increasing credit and extending the terms of loans. We believe that given that most of the government's goals and programmes, including credit lines, growth targets, the size of the fiscal deficit and so on, have not yet been formally announced. From this point of view, the technical level, counter-cyclical regulation of the space is also larger.

The policy choice of countercyclical regulation and its medium and long-term effects

There is no need to be overly pessimistic, but short-term economic growth is likely to suffer, given the tighter quarantine measures imposed in response to the outbreak. As noted above, although the duration is expected to be shorter, the impact on short-term year-on-year indicators is likely to be higher than during the SARS period. The outbreak of domestic and overseas aggregate demand in the short term may have a significant restraining effect, total output and price levels will be under pressure.

In view of the short-term growth is inevitably subject to more obvious shocks, timely and strong policy response is particularly important. Counter-cyclical policies are expected to stabilize growth and inflation expectations, prevent the corporate sector cash flow over-tightening, and "Base" employment. As the impact of demand growth may be "short and deep" , the government should give timely policy support to help enterprises and residents to tide over the difficulties.

In particular, monetary policy can be effective in easing financial conditions, especially in the affected reserve requirement, by reducing the size of the monetary policy pool, increasing liquidity provision, and reducing the financing costs for the real economy. On February 1, financial regulators jointly issued a notice saying they would maintain reasonable and ample liquidity, at the same time to reduce the cost of loans, increase credit loans, extend the duration of loans and other ways to support the impact of the larger enterprises affected by the epidemic. As during SARS, monetary policy will be eased to stabilize inflation expectations and ease cash flow pressures in the corporate sector.

Second, fiscal policy can reduce and delay taxes and fees paid by the corporate sector and provide targeted "bail-out funds" . As nominal growth is under short-term pressure, revenue growth may also temporarily decline and the so-called natural "stabilizers" of the broader deficit ratio will expand. Furthermore, reducing the tax burden on labour-intensive services would go a long way towards stabilizing investment and employment growth. In addition, targeted financial support ("bail-out funds") should be provided to the affected areas to facilitate the prevention and control of the epidemic and subsequent economic reconstruction.

In addition, industrial policies could be made more flexible to stabilize investment and employment growth. On the one hand, the policy could consider a more stringent control of the previously marginal relaxation, such as property development and some services. At the same time, the policy support for manufacturing investment may be increased appropriately, especially in promoting industrial upgrading and localization.

In addition to the short-term impact and response, the experience of the "new crown" epidemic will also help China to continue to improve its own disease prevention and control and medical system in the medium and long term. To its credit, the policy response to the outbreak has been decisive and effective. But the outbreak has also highlighted some areas where China's health system still needs improvement, including chronic shortages of health care workers and related supplies.

(the writer is head of research at CICC, Chief Economist, and Editor: Lu Ling)
